2026-04-16 12:20:09 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module indicator LEDs 1', 'Control module indicator LEDs 2', 'Control module indicator LEDs 3', 'Control module indicator LEDs 4', 'Control module indicator LEDs 5', 'Control module indicator LEDs 6', 'Control module indicator LEDs 7', 'Control module indicator LEDs 8', 'Load module main lamp', 'Load module internal indicator lamp'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU green LED confirms the 12 V source and its local wiring are functional. The external inspection has verified that all inter‑module cable pairs are correctly routed with no polarity inversion, all switches are closed, and the previously floating Control Input Cable (+) 6 has been seated so that the series 12 V path should now be continuous from PSU to load.\n\nDespite this, with a battery inserted and every switch ON, none of the series‑connected loads that should indicate current flow are illuminated: not a single control‑module LED (1–8) and neither of the two lamps in the load module (main lamp and parallel indicator). This combination of symptoms is most consistent with a common‑path open fault inside the load module or open filaments/devices in the actual light‑emitting components, rather than a remaining wiring error:\n\n- If the series 12 V line were interrupted somewhere upstream, at least one control‑module LED before that break would be able to light when its switch is ON (since its LED is wired across the local 12 V/0 V pair). Instead, **all** eight indicators are dark, and we have also discovered that their LED components are physically absent, meaning they cannot conduct or emit even if powered.\n- The load module contains the final current‑drawing elements (main lamp and internal indicator). With confirmed correct polarity (due to the diode orientation requirement) and no visible wiring defects, their failure to illuminate strongly suggests that at least one of these lamps is open or otherwise defective.\n\nGiven the constraints (multimeter unavailable and indicators physically missing), the most defensible explanation is that the indicator LEDs in all eight control modules are missing/failed open, and at least one of the lamps in the load module is also failed/open, so no visible element in the chain can light even though the PSU is operating and the series wiring has been restored.'
